Introduction to Age Dating

  • Age dating helps geologists determine the history of rock formations.
  • Relative age dating: Determines the sequence of events.
  • Absolute age dating: Assigns specific numerical ages.
  • Importance: Understanding Earthâs geological timeline.

Relative Age Dating

  • The relative age dating is used to determine the chronological order of geological events without assigning a numerical age.
  • Comparison of rock layers/unites to establish sequence.

Principles of relative age dating

  1. The Principle of Uniformitarianism
  2. Principle of Original Horizontality
  3. Principle of Superposition
  4. Principle of Lateral Continuity
  5. Law of Cross-Cutting Relationships
  6. Principle of Inclusions
  7. Principle of Faunal Succession

The Principle of Uniformitarianism

  • In 1785, James Hutton recognized that the present-day processes have operated throughout the geologic past.
  • ââThe present is the key to the pastââ _ For Example: the phenomena of gravity and magnetism operated in the past pretty much as they do so today

Principle of Original Horizontality

  • Sediments are deposited in horizontal layers.
  • Tilted layers indicate tectonic activity after deposition.

Principle (Law) of Superposition

  • In undisturbed sequences, the oldest layers are at the bottom, and the youngest at the top.

Principle of Lateral Continuity

  • The sediment extends laterally in all directions until it thins, pinches out, or terminates against the edge of the depositional basin
  • Under normal conditions, deposits originally extended in all directions

Law of Cross-Cutting Relationships

  • An intrusion (e.g., igneous) or fault that cuts through another rock is younger than the rock it cuts
  • Example: The intruding rock is always younger than the one it invades.

Principle of Inclusions

  • Rock fragments (inclusions) in a sedimentary layer must be older than the layer.
  • Example: Pebbles in a conglomerate must have existed before the conglomerate formed.

Principle of Faunal Succession

  • Fossils appear in a well-defined order through geological time.
  • Fossils can be used to establish relative age.

Absolute Age Dating

  • Absolute dating assigns numerical ages to rocks.
  • Based on isotopic dating methods.

Source: Jain, S. (2014)

Isotopic Dating Methods

  • Radioactive Decay: Radioactive elements break down over time, providing a clock for dating rocks.

    • Carbon-14 Dating: For recent fossils (up to ~50,000 years).
    • Uranium-Lead Dating: For older rocks (millions to billions of years).
    • Potassium-Argon Dating: Used for volcanic rocks.

Source: Jain, S. (2014)
